Causation is very difficult to assess using statistics of correlation .Usually, we try to define one variable as the independent or causal factor in a relationship and the other variable . For example :smoking tobacco(independent variable )is correlated and usually precedes getting cancer (dependent variable ) or another example is us politics ;women are more likely than men to vote for the democratic party , gender would be independent variable and their vote for president (democrat or republican) would be the dependent variable .

The actual correlation factor in the 1996 elections was 24.This means that if we know the gender of a person, we have a $24 \%$ vote better chance of predicting their vote than if we don't know their gender causes people to vote in different ways, it simply indicates that there is a relationship that may be causal in nature

