\section*{TYPES OF CORRELATION}

May be classified in different ways that include
1. Positive or negative
2. Simple, partial and multiple
3. Linear and non linear

\section*{POSITIVE CORRELATION}

Depends on direction of change on the variables. This may occur in two ways
-where one variable increase the other also increase
-where one decrease the other one also decrease
It is also referred to as direct correlation
Example
-variable x 10,12,15,18,or,80,70,60,40,40
-variable y $15,20,22,23,37$, or, $50,44,30,20,10$

\section*{NEGATIVE CORRELATION}

Variables vary in the positive direction such that where one variable increase the other one decreases and vice versa

Its also referred to as inverse
Example
-variable x $20,30,40,60,80$, or $100,90,60,40,30$
-variable y 40,30,22,15,10,or 10,20,30,40,30

\section*{SIMPLE, PARTIAL AND MULTIPLE CORRELATION}

Simple -only two variables are studies as above
Partial and multiple - three or more variables are studied
Partial- more than two variables are reorganized but only two are considered to influence each other .The possible influence from the others are kept constant

Multiple - three or more variables are studies simultaneously ie a drug test on the station , samples , amount used and effectiveness

\section*{LINEAR AND NON LINEAR}

These are correlation on the relation of change
The distinction between the two is based on the consistence of ratio change in the variables

Linear -is where change in one variable bear constant change in the other variable
Example
-variable x 10,20,30,40,50
-variable y 70,140,210,280,350
If the ratio is presented on the graph it gives a straight line

\section*{NON LINEAR}

Non linear - is where amount of change does not bear constant ratio of change to the other variable

It is also referred to as curvilinear
Double ratio of change in one does not necessarily mean double ratio in the other variable

